<div>
<p>âTo create that structure, to do those colours, and do nothing. I suddenly got what I wanted. It was just a way of pinning down the joy of colour<em>.</em>â<a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p>
<p>âUntitled (with Black Dot)â is the first spot painting on canvasÂ andÂ the only âPharmaceuticalâ painting (the most prolific sub-series of the spots) ever to have incorporated a black spot. Around the same time as creating the work on canvas, Hirst paintedÂ two near-identical arrangements of coloured spots onto the wall of the warehouse atÂ â<a href="/exhibitions/group/1988/freeze" target="_blank">Freeze</a>â. He called the worksÂ â<a href="/edge" target="_blank">Edge</a>â (1988) and â<a href="/row">Row</a>â (1988). These paintings followed some loose hand-painted spots on board, dating from 1986. Following âFreezeâ, Hirst started to refine the creative process. Slowly, he began to employ assistants to create the spot paintings. Any physical evidence of human intervention â such as the compass point left at the centre of each spot â was removed, until the works appeared to have been constructed mechanically, or âby a person trying to paint like a machineâ.<a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a>Â For Hirst, it was a departure from years of experimenting with paint and collage, and the first result of his search for a contemporary art form that could succeed without a reliance on âalready organised elements.âÂ </p>
<p>The random and infinite colour series within the âPharmaceuticalâ paintings is integral to the works. Hirst explains that, âmathematically, with the spot paintings, I probably discovered the most fundamentally important thing in any kind of art. Which is the harmony of where colour can exist on its own, interacting with other colours in a perfect format.â<a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a>Â Any problems he had previously had with colour, Hirst claims, were removed by the perfect arrangement of complimentary, yet never repeated, colours in the spots.</p>
<p>The spot paintings vary in size from a 40 foot canvas containing spots of 1 inch, â<a href="/iodomethane-13c" target="_blank">Iodomethane- 13c</a>â (1999 - 2000), to âErbium Oxideâ (2009), which has only four 60 inch spots, to âL-Isoleucinolâ (2008 - 2011), which measures ten by sixteen inches and contains 25,781 one millimeter spots. Their titles are taken arbitrarily from the chemical company Sigma-Aldrichâs catalogue âBiochemicals for Research and Diagnostic Reagentsâ, a book Hirst stumbled across in the early 1990âs. The grid formula within the âPharmaceuticalâ paintings was the basis for an endless series. Over the last 24 years, Hirst has produced on average 60 spot paintings a year.Â </p>
<p>In 2012 Gagosian Gallery exhibited over 300 spot paintings across eleven gallery spaces worldwide. Conceived as a single exhibition, â<a href="/exhibitions/solo/2012/complete-spot-paintings" target="_blank">The Complete Spot Paintings 1986-2011</a>â fulfilled Hirstâs longstanding ambition to show the works together. He explained in 2000, âitâs an assault on your senses. They grab hold of you and give you a good shaking. As adults, weâre not used to it. Itâs an amazing fact that all objects leap beyond their own dimension.â<a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p>
